void main() {
  // lists in dart
  
  // okay list is actually arrays, dart just likes to call it lists cause it stores a list of things. there are two types of lists. 1. constant list and 2. variable list. we will be looking at variable lists. 
  
  // so first create a list, it can be anything like numbers or strings and can be long or short however you like.
  var newList = [1, 2, 3];
  
  //now we can print it
  print(newList);
  
  // if you want to like print an item at a specific location in the list , you can specify the location as indexes, same as arrays and you know that arrays start from index 0.
  
  print(newList[1]);
  
  // we can change items in it as well
  //what you need to do is write the name of the list and pass the "index of the item" we wanna change and = the item we want. like this: newList[index of item need to be changed] = item we want
  
  newList[0] = 3;
  print(newList);
  
  //we can also create an empty list
  
  var emptyList = [];
  
  print(emptyList);
  
  // since we created an empty list, we need to add items in it as well right ? so for that we will use add function.
  
  emptyList.add(0);
  print(emptyList);
  
  //we can add multiple items as well
  
  emptyList.addAll([1, 2, 7]);
  print(emptyList);
  
  //what if we wanna add an item at a specific position ? for that we will use the insert function. insert function allows you to add things at a specific position: insert(position, item)
  
  emptyList.insert(3, 3);
  print(emptyList);
  
  //like addAll there is a function called insertAll, it allows you to insert multiple values starting from a specific positiom. like you wanna add values [9, 10 ,11] at the position 1 the array will be [0, 9, 10 ,11, 1, 2, 3, 4] you cannot add multiple values at different specific positions thou like you wanna add 9 at the end, 10 in the middle and 11 somewhere anywhere. that is not possible.
  
  emptyList.insertAll(4, [4, 5, 6]);
  print(emptyList);
  
  //you can also create a mixed list here
  
  var mixedList = [1, 2, "John", 3, 4, "Bob", 5, "Bob"];
  
  print(mixedList);
  
  //now remove items, you can do that by using remove function and writing the value(not the index) you want to remove.
  
  mixedList.remove("John");
  print(mixedList);
  
  //okay that's good. what if there are multiple Johns or multiple 5s what then ? then we can use removeAt function but to use it, it is necessary to know the location of the item you need to remove. in our case i wanna remove the Bob at the end so it's position is 6 after removing John so i will write
  
  mixedList.removeAt(6);
  print(mixedList);
  
  mixedList.removeAt(4);
  print(mixedList);
  
  //okay one last thing, let's say we have the same value multiple times and instead of using removeAt we use remove function. what will happen then ? let's check with an example.
  
  //create a new list
  var example = [0, 1, 2, "bob", "bob", 3, "bob", 4, 5];
  
  print(example);
  
  example.remove("bob"); 
  
  // what do you think it will do ?
  
  print(example);
  
  //output: [0, 1, 2, bob, 3, bob, 4, 5]. it removed only the first bob and left everything as is. but let's say we wanna remove all the bobs fromthe lsit. for that there is a function in dart that is a tiny bit advanced cause no one teaches it at a beginner level. the function is called removeWhere
  
  example.removeWhere((element) => element == "bob");
  
  // this will remove all the bobs from the list.
  
  print(example);
  
  // output: [0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5]
}
